In this assignment, we are going to study test scores from the The Programme for International Student Assessment (PISA) scheme, which tests 15-year-old students across all states in Australia. You can find the data sets and a code book for the assignment in the Data folder. Broadly speaking, PISA measures scholastic ability across three categories: science, reading and math.

The goal of this analysis is to understand if differences exist between PISA testing scores across various dimensions, such as income, school type, extra-curricular activities and gender.

Question 2: Calculate the average math, science and read score across states. (2pts) Create a table where you display the top 3 states that have highest average in math. (2pts)

mean_scores <- pisa %>%
  group_by(state) %>%   #1pt
  summarise(mean_math = mean(math, na.rm = TRUE),mean_science = mean(science, na.rm = TRUE),mean_read = mean(read, na.rm = TRUE))  # 1pt
mean_scores %>%
  arrange(-mean_math) %>%  #1pt
  head(3)   #1pt
## # A tibble: 3 × 4
##   state mean_math mean_science mean_read
##   <chr>     <dbl>        <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 ACT        501.         523.      511.
## 2 WA         496.         512.      499.
## 3 VIC        495.         509.      504.

Question 3: For female students born in 1999, which type of school had the highest average performce in math, science and read (2pts). And for students born in 2000? (1pt)

top_marks_1999 <- pisa %>%
  group_by(schtype) %>%  #0.5pt
  dplyr::filter(gender=="female", birthyr == 1999) %>%  #0.5pt
  summarise(mean_math = mean(math, na.rm = TRUE),mean_science = mean(science, na.rm = TRUE),mean_read = mean(read, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%   #0.5pt
  arrange(-mean_math)  #0.5pt
top_marks_2000 <- pisa %>%
  group_by(schtype) %>%  #0.5pt
  dplyr::filter(gender=="female", birthyr == 2000) %>%  #0.5pt
  summarise(mean_math = mean(math, na.rm = TRUE),mean_science = mean(science, na.rm = TRUE),mean_read = mean(read, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%   #0.5pt
  arrange(-mean_math)

In the year 1999, the school type with the highest mean maths, science and read scores for female gender was school type “Ind” while in the year 2000 is also “Ind”.

Question 4: For the states of VIC, NSW, and QLD, using geom_density plot the distribution of marks in read by gender using a faceted plot to capture school type (2pt). Which combination of states/schools do female students perform worst in? (2pt).

pl1 <- ggplot(data=pisa %>% filter(state %in% c('VIC','NSW','QLD')), aes(x=read,fill=schtype)) + 
  geom_density(alpha=0.5) + 
  facet_wrap(~gender+state) +
  labs(fill='School type')
print(pl1)

According to the above density plot, Government schools in the state of New South Wales (NSW) were observed to report low read scores for females.

Question 5: First, create a data frame called pisa_filtered that excludes observations with missing values among any variable (2pt). Then, calculate a new variable called tot_score that is the sum of the math/science/reading scores and add this to the data frame pisa_filtered (1pt); in addition, calculate a new variable tot_time as the sum of the math_time/read_time/science_time and add this new variable to the data frame pisa_filtered (1pt). Using a geom_point() describe the relationship between tot_time (x-axis) and tot_score (y-axis). (2pts)

pisa_filtered <- drop_na(pisa) #(2pt)


pisa_filtered<-pisa_filtered %>%
  dplyr::mutate(tot_score = math+science+read) %>%   #1pt
  dplyr::mutate(tot_time = math+science_time+read_time)   #1pt

pisa_filtered %>%  ggplot(aes(y=tot_score,x=tot_time))+geom_point() + geom_smooth(method='lm' ) #(2pt)

As we can observe from the above plot, a linear relationship is observed between the total scores and total times. This suggests that students who have devoting greater amount of time in the subjects of maths,science and read are observed to score higher scores in these subjects.

Question 6. Let us try and understand the importance of extracurricular activities on marks. Which category of music_instr has the highest median score in reading, math, and science. Present your results as a table.(2pt) Looking at the table, what can you conclude about the usefullness of musical instruments on test scores? (1pt).

extra_curr <- pisa_filtered %>% group_by(music_instr) %>% summarise(Median_tot_score =median(tot_score)) %>% arrange(-Median_tot_score)
extra_curr %>% kable(caption = 'Music instrument category for highest median total scores',booktabs = TRUE) %>% 
kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("bordered","hover"))
Music instrument category for highest median total scores
music_instr Median_tot_score
4 1641.615
3 1578.802
2 1544.328
1 1485.898

The above table shows that the median total score is higher for students who have learnt more number of musical instruments. Hence, musical instruments are indeed important for total scores.

Question 7: Describe the relationship between median scores and music instruments (1pt)? Is the effect the same for both genders? (2pt)

extra_curr_gender <- pisa_filtered %>% group_by(music_instr,gender) %>% summarise(Median_tot_score =median(tot_score)) %>% arrange(-Median_tot_score)
pl2 <- ggplot(data= extra_curr_gender,aes(x=music_instr,y=Median_tot_score,color=gender)) + geom_line(size=2,linetype='dashed') + geom_point(size=5) + labs(color='Gender')
print(pl2)

As we can see from the above plot, as number of instruments increase, the median total scores also increase. Hence, a direct proportional linear relationship is observed between the two variables. The relationship is observed to be consistent for both the male and female gender.

Question 8. Your analysis has so far yielded several variables that may influence test scores, such as gender, music_instr, and what type of school the student is from, schtype. However, there are many other variables that we may have missed. As a first step in understanding these variables, we can cluster the data to try and see if any patterns emerge beyond those already seen. Use k-means clustering on the following variables with \(k=5\) clusters: gender, music_instr, internet_use, sport, belong, anxtest, motivat, wealth, read, tot_time, and tot_score.(3pt) Report the number of elements in each cluster.(2pt) Hint: You will need to create a categorical variable for gender. This can be done using mutate and ifelse.

df_new<- pisa_filtered %>% mutate(num_gender = if_else(gender == "female", 1, 0)) %>% select(num_gender,music_instr,internet_use,sport,belong,anxtest,motivat,wealth, internet_use, read,tot_time, tot_score) #(1pt)

m<-ncol(df_new) #(1pt)

# Solution for $k=5$
kmeans_basic <- kmeans(df_new,centers = 5,nstart=20)
kmeans_basic_df <- data.frame(Clusters = kmeans_basic$cluster, df_new) #(1pt)

#Number in each Cluster
kmeans_basic_df %>% group_by(Clusters) %>% count() #(2pt)
